Introduction

restrict <- T

if (restrict) {
  samples <- sort(colSums(is.na(prot.mat)))[1:6] %>%
    names()
} else {
  samples <- sort(colSums(is.na(prot.mat))) %>%
    names()
}

prot.mat <- prot.mat[, samples]

colors.use <- colors.chosen[samples]

meta <- meta[rownames(meta) %in% samples, ]

## Filter out fully NA rows
idx <- rowSums(is.na(prot.mat)) == ncol(prot.mat)
prot.mat <- prot.mat[!idx, ]

## Creating MSnSet using the crosstab and metadata
m <- MSnSet(exprs = prot.mat, pData = meta[colnames(prot.mat), ])
params.NA <- c(0.2, 0.4, 0.6)
params.pseudoNA <- c(0.1, 0.1, 0.1)

Below we have the metadata for this experiment. We have a total of 10 samples and 1790 Proteins. In this initial analysis we compare the Pre and Post groups, and investigate whether the imputation of the missing values is meaningful.

PCA plots

Note that only the 402 proteins with no missing data can be used when making a PCA plot.

p <- plot_pca_v4(m, "Trametinib", show.ellipse = F) +
  ggtitle("PCA by Treatment") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 13, hjust = 0.5))

p

\[\\[.2in]\]

Pre-Trametinib vs Post-Trametinib

Next, we compare the Pre and Post treatment groups within each cell type individually. Due to the large amount of missing data, we first restrict the samples by cell type, then filter the proteins such that at most 60% of the data is missing within that cell type.

Imputation

Next, we try to test how far off imputed values are from their original observed values. We do this by introducing NEW NA values to the dataset at random, which we call pseudo NA values. We then compare the value imputed for the pseudo NA values to the original observed value. We do this a few times, filtering the original dataset at different levels each time.

Differential Expression & GSEA

Using these proteins, we compare the pre and post-treatment group using differential expression and rank based GSEA with the KEGG database.

show <- limma %>%
  select(-featureID, -t, -B, -AveExpr) %>% head(.)
kbl(show) %>%
  kable_paper("hover", full_width = F)

At most 20% missing per protein, 10% pseudo NA introduced.

We filter the original data to have at most 20% of its entries per protein as NA values. We then randomly choose 10% of the present intensities and replace them with NA values. Our imputed dataset has 560 proteins in total. Below we see the distribution of the differences between the imputed (pseudo NA) values and the original values.

The mean squared error between the imputed pseudo NA values and the original values is 1.4114191.
